00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:01.000
ABOUT HOW THE
EARTH WILL BEHAVE;

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:03.000
PREDICTIONS THAT CAN
SAVE LIVES AND CONSERVE

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:06.000
VALUABLE RESOURCES
FOR FUTURE GENERATIONS.

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:18.000
AFTER PREPARING A HOT
CUP OF TEA, MAYA TOLSTOY

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:21.000
IS READY TO PROBE THE
DEPTHS OF THE OCEAN.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:23.000
SITTING AT HER COMPUTER
IS THE ONLY WAY FOR HER

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:26.000
TO STUDY UNDERWATER
VOLCANOES AND EARTHQUAKES.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:29.000
NOBODY'S EVER SEEN THOSE
EARTHQUAKES BEFORE,

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:32.000
NOBODY KNOWS WHAT PROCESSES
ARE HAPPENING THERE,

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:33.000
DEEP IN THE OCEAN.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:36.000
EVEN THOUGH YOU'RE VERY
OFTEN AT THE DESK,

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:37.000
IT'S LIKE EXPLORATION.

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:40.000
WITH TWO-THIRDS OF THE
PLANET COVERED BY WATER,

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:43.000
MARINE SEISMOLOGISTS HAVE
A LOT OF AREA TO COVER

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:45.000
WHILE STUDYING AND
MONITORING THE UNDERWATER

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:46.000
EARTHQUAKES
AND VOLCANOES

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:48.000
THAT SHAPE OUR
EARTH'S CRUST.

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:50.000
LEARNING MORE ABOUT THESE
POWERFUL EVENTS COULD LEAD

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:52.000
TO BETTER WARNINGS ABOUT
THEIR POTENTIAL EFFECTS

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:55.000
ON LAND - LIKE THE
DEVASTATION CAUSED BY

00:02:55.000 --> 00:02:57.000
THE 2004
TSUNAMI IN ASIA.

00:02:57.000 --> 00:02:59.000
MAYA IS ONE OF THE
SCIENTISTS WHO STUDIED

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:02.000
THE EARTHQUAKE THAT
CAUSED THE TSUNAMI.

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:04.000
SHE DISCOVERED HOW LARGE
THE QUAKE ACTUALLY WAS

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:07.000
BY ANALYZING THE SOUND WAVES
IT RELEASED INTO THE OCEAN.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:10.000
IT'S A VERY EERIE
SOUND, OBVIOUSLY.

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:16.000
IT DEFINITELY SENDS
SHIVERS DOWN YOUR SPINE.

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:20.000
IT'S THE SOUND OF THE EARTH
RIPPING APART FOR THAT LONG.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:23.000
IT WENT A DISTANCE
BASICALLY THE LENGTH

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:29.000
OF CALIFORNIA, 750 MILES,
IN EIGHT MINUTES.

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:31.000
BUT MAYA'S WORK ALSO
REQUIRES HER TO DO

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:34.000
PLENTY OF ACTUAL EXPLORING
- LIKE SAILING INTO

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:37.000
THE OPEN OCEAN TO DEPLOY
INSTRUMENTS THAT MONITOR

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:39.000
THE EARTH'S MOVEMENT
AND RECORD THE SOUND

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:41.000
OF THE UNDERWATER
EVENTS SHE STUDIES.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:44.000
THE FIRST CRUISE I WENT ON
WAS A 10-DAY CRUISE

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:47.000
WHEN I WAS AN UNDERGRADUATE,
AND IT WAS JUST MAGICAL.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:50.000
BEING FAR AWAY FROM LAND
AND THE SMELL OF THE OCEAN,

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:53.000
THERE'S A REALLY NICE
TEAM SPIRIT THAT DEVELOPS,

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:56.000
IT'S A GREAT ADVENTURE;
IT'S VERY EXCITING.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:00.000
MAYA STILL GOES ON CRUISES
AT LEAST ONCE A YEAR,

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:03.000
THOUGH AS A SENIOR SCIENTIST
SHE HAS THE OPTION

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:05.000
OF SENDING OTHERS
IN HER PLACE

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:06.000
WHICH GIVES HER
MORE TIME AT HOME

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:08.000
WITH HER SON, JASON.

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:10.000
IT'S A LUXURY SHE'S EARNED
THROUGH HARD WORK,

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:12.000
BUT IT WASN'T
ALWAYS EASY.

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:14.000
MAYA RECALLS ONE
PARTICULAR RUN-IN

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:17.000
WITH HER SENIOR-YEAR
SCIENCE TEACHER.

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:20.000
HE HEARD ONE DAY THAT
I'D APPLIED FOR COLLEGE

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:23.000
TO DO PHYSICS, AND
HE SCREAMED AT ME

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:24.000
IN FRONT OF THE WHOLE
CLASS, AND HE SAID,

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:27.000
"YOU'RE NOT GONNA MAKE
IT PAST YOUR FIRST YEAR,

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:29.000
YOUR MOMMY'S NOT
GONNA BE THERE,

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:31.000
GIRLS DON'T
DO PHYSICS!"

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:33.000
JUST TOTALLY
HUMILIATED ME

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:35.000
IN FRONT OF
THE WHOLE CLASS.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:36.000
BUT I WENT ANYWAY.

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:39.000
GETTING THROUGH THE ROAD
BLOCKS HAS BEEN WORTH IT.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:41.000
MAYA IS NOW A TOP
SCIENTIST IN HER FIELD

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:44.000
AND SHE EVEN FINDS TIME TO
PURSUE HER OTHER PASSION:

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:45.000
ACTING.

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:48.000
I'M STILL IN THE SCREEN
ACTORS GUILD, SO I PAY

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:51.000
MY MEMBERSHIP CAUSE
I'M NOT GIVING THAT UP.

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:56.000
I ALSO DID A DOCUMENTARY
WITH JAMES CAMERON CALLED

00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:59.000
ALIENS OF THE DEEP , AND
SO THAT WAS REALLY FUN.

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:01.000
IN FACT, SHE SAYS
THE TWO CAREERS

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:03.000
AREN'T ALL
THAT DIFFERENT.

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:05.000
ONE OF THE THINGS I REALLY
LIKED ABOUT ACTING WAS THE

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:08.000
TEAMWORK THAT GOES INTO
MAKING A PRODUCTION.

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:09.000
AND THAT'S ONE
OF THE THINGS

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:11.000
I REALLY ENJOY
ABOUT SCIENCE

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:13.000
AND ABOUT DOING THE
BIG SEA-GOING PROJECTS.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:16.000
HER WORK BACK ON LAND -
ANALYZING PATTERNS

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:18.000
IN THE DATA FROM HER
SEA INSTRUMENTS -

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:20.000
CAN BE MORE LIKE TRYING
TO SOLVE A PUZZLE.

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:22.000
HER BACKGROUND
IN SCIENCE

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:24.000
HAS EQUIPPED HER
FOR THIS CHALLENGE,

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:26.000
AND ALSO PREPARED
HER FOR SO MUCH MORE.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:29.000
ONE OF THE THINGS THAT
SCIENCE TEACHES YOU IS

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:32.000
CRITICAL THINKING AND
LOGICAL THINKING AND

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:34.000
I THINK THAT THAT'S JUST
SUCH A VALUABLE SKILL

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:36.000
IN ANY ASPECT OF LIFE,

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:39.000
WHETHER YOU'RE LISTENING
TO AN AD FOR A CAR

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:42.000
OR WHETHER YOU'RE
LISTENING TO POLITICIANS,

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:44.000
IT'S ALWAYS
VALUABLE TO HAVE

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:47.000
GOOD CRITICAL
THINKING SKILLS.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:56.000
MARINE SEISMOLOGISTS
SPEND A LOT OF TIME

00:05:56.000 --> 00:05:59.000
OUT ON THE OCEAN AND
NEED A STRONG BACKGROUND

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:01.000
IN PHYSICS AND GEOLOGY.

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:05.000
RESEARCH AREAS INCLUDE
STUDYING TSUNAMIS

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:07.000
AND THE MOVEMENT OF
THE EARTH'S CRUST.

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:09.000
COMMERCIALLY,
MARINE SEISMOLOGISTS

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:13.000
CAN WORK IN THE
PETROCHEMICAL INDUSTRY.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:16.000
RECENT GRADUATES CAN
EXPECT STARTING SALARIES

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:18.000
OF $36,000 A YEAR.

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:20.000
THE MEDIAN SALARY
FOR ALL SEISMOLOGISTS

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:23.000
IS OVER $67,000 A YEAR.

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:35.000
MOST PEOPLE HEAD FOR
SAFETY WHEN A HURRICANE

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:39.000
IS HEADED FOR LANDFALL,
BUT NOT STAN GOLDENBERG.

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:41.000
HE GETS INTO A PLANE
AND FLIES RIGHT INTO

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:43.000
THE EYE OF THE STORM.

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:44.000
STAN IS A
METEOROLOGIST

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:46.000
WITH THE HURRICANE
RESEARCH DIVISION

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:48.000
OF THE U.S.
GOVERNMENT'S NATIONAL

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:51.000
OCEANIC AND ATMOSPHERIC
ADMINISTRATION, OR NOAA.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:53.000
AS ONE OF THEIR
"HURRICANE HUNTERS",

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:55.000
IT'S HIS JOB TO GO ON
RECONNAISANCE FLIGHTS

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:58.000
BEFORE AND DURING
HURRICANES.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:00.000
IN NOAA'S SPECIALLY
EQUIPPED PLANES,

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:03.000
HE CAPTURES DATA THAT HELPS
ESTIMATE THE SIZE,

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:05.000
SPEED AND LIKELY
PATH OF THE STORM -

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:07.000
INFORMATION THAT'S
CRITICAL TO ASSESSING

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:10.000
THE NEED FOR WARNINGS
AND EVACUATIONS.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:13.000
I'VE FLOWN THROUGH
THE EYE OF STORMS

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:15.000
OVER A HUNDRED
TIMES BEFORE THAT,

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:16.000
BUT IT'S NOTHING
IN THE AIR

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:18.000
LIKE IT IS
ON THE GROUND.

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:20.000
AND STAN WOULD KNOW.

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:23.000
IN 1992 HE AND HIS FAMILY
ENDURED THE FURY

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:25.000
OF HURRICANE ANDREW.

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:31.000
THE ROOF LIFTED OFF,
 AND AS YOU CAN SEE,

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:33.000
WE HAVE NO HOUSE.

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:38.000
THANKING GOD, THANKING
 GOD THAT WERE ALL SAFE.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:42.000
HALLELUJAH.

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:44.000
AS ANDREW APPROACHED,
STAN'S WIFE GAVE BIRTH

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:46.000
TO THEIR DAUGHTER PEARL.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:48.000
KNOWING THAT WIFE AND
BABY WOULD BE SAFE IN THE

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:50.000
HOSPITAL, STAN HEADED
TO THEIR MIAMI HOME

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:53.000
TO RIDE OUT THE STORM
WITH THEIR THREE SONS.

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:55.000
IT WAS A NIGHT THEY
ALMOST DIDN'T SURVIVE.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:07:57.000
GOING THROUGH THAT
TERRIFYING EXPERIENCE

00:07:57.000 --> 00:07:59.000
GIVES ME A LOT MORE
COMPASSION FOR OTHER

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:01.000
PEOPLE WHO MIGHT GO
THROUGH THESE THINGS

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:04.000
IN THE CARIBBEAN AND
OTHER PARTS OF THE U.S.,

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:05.000
AND I URGE PEOPLE:

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:09.000
THEY MUST TAKE
HURRICANES SERIOUSLY.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:11.000
SINCE THEN STAN HAS BECOME
A LEADING ADVOCATE

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:13.000
FOR HURRICANE
PREPAREDNESS,

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:15.000
GIVING PUBLIC TALKS
ON WHAT TO DO.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:18.000
ON THE RESEARCH SIDE, HE
SPECIALIZES IN FORECASTING

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:21.000
LONG-RANGE HURRICANE
ACTIVITY IN THE ATLANTIC.

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:25.000
IN 2001, STAN CO-AUTHORED
A LANDMARK SCIENTIFIC PAPER

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:27.000
PREDICTING THAT THE
NUMBER OF HURRICANES

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:28.000
MAKING LANDFALL
IN THE U.S.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:30.000
WOULD INCREASE
DRAMATICALLY.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:32.000
BY ANALYZING
WEATHER PATTERNS

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:34.000
AND CORRELATING THOSE
TO HURRICANE ACTIVITY,

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:37.000
STAN PREDICTED THE U.S.
WAS ENTERING A NATURAL

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:39.000
CYCLE OF INTENSIFIED
HURRICANE ACTIVITY.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:42.000
I SAID, MAYBE THIS ISN'T
JUST A LITTLE SPIKE,

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:44.000
MAYBE THIS IS
A LONG-TERM TREND.

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:46.000
THE NEXT SEVERAL HURRICANE
SEASONS SEEMED TO CONFIRM

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:49.000
HIS FINDINGS, WITH
POWERFUL STORMS LIKE

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:53.000
DENNIS, RITA, WILMA
AND, OF COURSE, KATRINA.

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:56.000
NO FORECAST - SEASONAL
FORECAST OR LONG-TERM

00:08:56.000 --> 00:08:59.000
FORECAST LIKE THIS - CAN
TELL ANY REGION WITH ANY

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:02.000
CERTAINTY THAT YOU'RE
GOING TO GET HIT ANY TIME

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:05.000
IN THE NEXT TWO OR
THREE YEARS OR SOMETHING.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:07.000
BUT IT CERTAINLY SAYS
THERE'S MORE OF A

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:10.000
PROBABILITY OF IT - THERE'S
MORE ARROWS OUT THERE.

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:12.000
STAN'S CAREER IS PROOF
THAT IT'S NEVER TOO LATE

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:14.000
TO CHANGE YOUR MIND.

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:15.000
HE DROPPED OUT
OF JUNIOR COLLEGE

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:17.000
TO HITCHHIKE
ACROSS THE COUNTRY.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:19.000
BUT HIS EXPERIENCES
CONVINCED HIM

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:21.000
TO RETURN HOME
AND TRY AGAIN.

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:23.000
HE ENDED UP IN A
METEOROLOGY PROGRAM

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:26.000
AND JOINED NOAA AFTER
COMPLETING HIS MASTER'S.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:29.000
GIVEN THE DISASTER THAT
CAN STRIKE WHEN PEOPLE

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:31.000
FAIL TO EVACUATE,
IT'S EASY TO SEE WHY

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:34.000
STAN'S HURRICANE HUNTER
FLIGHTS ARE IMPORTANT.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:35.000
BUT IT'S ALSO
IMPORTANT TO FIGURE OUT

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:37.000
WHEN NOT TO EVACUATE.

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:40.000
MOST PEOPLE DON'T
KNOW IT COSTS

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:42.000
ABOUT ONE MILLION
DOLLARS PER COASTLINE

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:45.000
OF POPULATED
AREA TO EVACUATE.

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:49.000
SO IF WE CAN REDUCE THE
WARNING AREA BY JUST

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:51.000
ONE MILE, AS FAR AS
THE AREA EVACUATED,

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:54.000
WE'VE PAID FOR OUR PROGRAM
FOR THE WHOLE YEAR.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:57.000
AND ASIDE FROM GATHERING
SUCH CRITICAL DATA,

00:09:57.000 --> 00:09:59.000
FLYING INTO THE EYE
OF A HURRICANE

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:01.000
HAS OTHER REWARDS.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:03.000
IT'S SPECTACULAR BEAUTY.

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:05.000
AWESOME BEAUTY
FROM SEA TO SKY.

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:08.000
TALK ABOUT A 10-MILE-HIGH
WALL OF CLOUDS

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:11.000
CIRCLING AROUND YOU,
BUT CLEAR AT THE TOP,

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:13.000
CALM OCEAN
AT THE BOTTOM,

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:16.000
AND PEOPLE'S MOUTHS
USUALLY DROP OPEN

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:19.000
EVEN IF YOU'VE BEEN IN
THERE AGAIN AND AGAIN.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:28.000
METEOROLOGISTS NEED
A FOUNDATION IN MATH

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:31.000
AND PHYSICS, SOME KNOWLEDGE
OF COMPUTER PROGRAMMING,

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:34.000
AND IN SOME CASES, AN
UNDERSTANDING OF CHEMISTRY.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:36.000
TELEVISION WEATHER
FORECASTERS MAY GET

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:39.000
ALL THE GLORY, BUT
THOSE GIGS ARE RARE.

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:41.000
MOST JOBS ARE WITHIN
FEDERAL AGENCIES, AND

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:44.000
THERE ARE ALSO
METEOROLOGY JOBS IN THE

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:47.000
OIL, AERONAUTICS AND
INSURANCE INDUSTRIES.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:50.000
IN FEDERAL AGENCIES,
ENTRY-LEVEL PAY FOR

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:53.000
COLLEGE GRADUATES IS
ABOUT $28,000 A YEAR.

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:56.000
THE MEDIAN ANNUAL SALARY
FOR ALL METEOROLOGISTS

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:59.000
IS ABOUT $70,000.

