JAKE LOWENSTERN

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:18.000
LEARNED A
VALUABLE LESSON:

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:20.000
CHECK THE DAILY
SEISMIC RECORDS

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:23.000
BEFORE YOU HEAD UP THE
SIDE OF AN ACTIVE VOLCANO.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:25.000
JAKE AND HIS GUIDE
WERE PREPARING

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:27.000
TO TAKE SAMPLES
OF NEW LAVA FLOW

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:29.000
WHEN THE SITUATION
SUDDENLY TURNED DANGEROUS.

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:32.000
THEY HAD TO BEAT A HASTY
RETREAT IN THE DARK

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:34.000
ACROSS A WEEK-OLD
MOLTEN LAVA FLOW.

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:37.000
HAD WE KNOWN MORE, WE
WOULDN'T HAVE BEEN THERE.

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:42.000
AND WE WERE DODGING BOMBS
OF LAVA THAT WERE SHOOTING

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:45.000
INTO THE SKY AND
FALLING ALL AROUND US.

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:47.000
IT WAS A TRULY
TERRIFYING EXPERIENCE

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:50.000
- NOT ONE THAT I HOPE
TO EVER HAVE AGAIN,

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:53.000
BUT ONE FROM WHICH
I LEARNED A LOT.

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:56.000
BUT HANDS-ON WORK IN THE
FIELD IS JUST WHAT JAKE

00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:59.000
WAS LOOKING FOR WHEN HE
CHOSE GEOLOGY AS A CAREER.

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:01.000
TODAY, JAKE READS
SEISMIC RECORDS

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:03.000
LIKE MOST OF US READ
THE LOCAL PAPER.

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:05.000
AS A RESEARCH
GEOLOGIST AT THE U.S.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:08.000
GEOLOGICAL SURVEY AND THE
SCIENTIST-IN-CHARGE OF THE

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:10.000
YELLOWSTONE VOLCANO
OBSERVATORY, HE HEADS UP A

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:13.000
TEAM OF SCIENTISTS AND
RESEARCHERS THAT MONITORS

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:15.000
VOLCANIC ACTIVITY IN
THE NATIONAL PARK.

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:17.000
YELLOWSTONE IS HOME TO
ONE OF THE COUNTRY'S

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:20.000
MOST ACTIVE CALDERAS: A
VOLCANO THAT HAS COLLAPSED

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:22.000
INTO THE GROUND.

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:24.000
I GET TO WALK AROUND
THE VOLCANOES,

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:27.000
I STUDY THE GASES THAT
COME OUT OF THE GROUND,

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:30.000
AND I GET TO WORK ON HOT
SPRINGS AND WATCH MAGMA

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:33.000
AND LAVA COMING OUT OF
THE GROUND, AND IT'S

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:36.000
A PRETTY TREMENDOUS
THING TO GET TO DO.

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:38.000
AFTER GRADUATING FROM
COLLEGE WITH A BACHELOR'S

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:40.000
DEGREE IN GEOLOGY, JAKE
SPENT A YEAR IN SICILY

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:43.000
DOING RESEARCH AT MOUNT
ETNA, ONE OF THE WORLD'S

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:46.000
MOST FAMOUS
ACTIVE VOLCANOES.

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:49.000
IT WAS A GREAT YEAR FOR
ME PERSONALLY AND AS A

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:52.000
SCIENTIST LEARNING WHAT
HAPPENS ON A BIG VOLCANO

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:55.000
THAT'S SURROUNDED
BY CITIES.

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:57.000
MUCH OF JAKE'S RESEARCH
TODAY IS INFLUENCED

00:12:57.000 --> 00:12:59.000
BY THAT EXPERIENCE.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:01.000
WHILE MANY VOLCANOLOGISTS
CONCENTRATE ON MAPPING

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:03.000
VOLCANOS AND RESEARCHING
THEIR HISTORY,

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:07.000
JAKE FOCUSES ON MONITORING
VOLCANIC ACTIVITY.

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:09.000
HE COLLECTS AND MEASURES
GASES EMANATING

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:11.000
FROM VOLCANIC AREAS,
AND USES THE DATA

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:14.000
TO FORECAST
POTENTIAL ERUPTIONS.

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:16.000
WHILE IT'S IMPOSSIBLE TO
PREDICT WITH CERTAINTY

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:18.000
WHAT VOLCANOES
WILL DO,

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:21.000
THEY DO OFFER CLUES DAYS,
WEEKS OR EVEN MONTHS

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:24.000
BEFORE MAGMA ACTUALLY
MAKES IT TO THE SURFACE.

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:27.000
GENERALLY BEFORE ANY KIND
OF VOLCANIC ERUPTION OCCURS

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:30.000
THE VOLCANO SENDS OUT
SIGNALS THAT WE CAN READ

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:32.000
TO KNOW THAT
SOMETHING IS HAPPENING,

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:35.000
THAT SOMETHING
NEEDS CLOSER WATCHING.

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:37.000
AND SO THOSE ARE THE SORTS
OF THINGS THAT WE DO

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:39.000
AS VOLCANO
OBSERVATORIES

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:42.000
TO PREPARE FOR
COMING ERUPTIONS.

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:45.000
AN AVID WRITER, JAKE
HAS ALSO SERVED AS

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:47.000
A CONSULTANT ON SEVERAL
DOCUMENTARIES AND FILMS.

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:49.000
HE TRAVELS ABOUT TWO
MONTHS OUT OF THE YEAR,

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:51.000
EXPLORING THE
YELLOWSTONE CALDERA

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:54.000
AND VISITING VOLCANOES
AROUND THE WORLD.

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:57.000
A RECENT TRIP TOOK HIM TO
ITALY'S PHLEGRAEN FIELDS,

00:13:57.000 --> 00:13:59.000
WHERE HE WAS AMAZED BY
HOW AN ENTIRE COMMUNITY

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:02.000
EXISTS WITHIN THE
VOLCANIC SYSTEM.

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:04.000
I'VE BEEN TO A LOT OF
DIFFERENT COUNTRIES,

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:06.000
I'VE BEEN TO SOME OF THE
HIGHEST PLACES ON EARTH

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:09.000
AND SOME OF THE
DEEPEST VALLEYS

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:11.000
AND SOME OF THE
RICHEST COUNTRIES

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:13.000
AND SOME OF THE POOREST
PLACES ON EARTH.

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:15.000
I'VE JUST BEEN ABLE TO
SEE A LOT AND LEARN A LOT

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:18.000
ABOUT WHAT HAPPENS HERE
AND IN OTHER PLACES

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:21.000
BESIDES WHERE I LIVE, SO
IT'S ALWAYS AN EDUCATION;

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:25.000
IT'S SOMETHING
THAT I LOVE TO DO.

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:27.000
BUT EVEN WITH ALL THE
TRAVEL, FIELD WORK

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:30.000
AND HANDS-ON EXPERIENCES,
JAKE'S GREATEST SATISFACTION

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:33.000
COMES FROM SHARING THE
RESULTS OF HIS RESEARCH -

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:36.000
WRITING CLEAR, CONCISE PAPERS
THAT ADD TO OUR KNOWLEDGE

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:38.000
OF VOLCANOES AND THEIR
EFFECT ON THE EARTH.

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:41.000
THIS IS WHERE WE LIVE;
IT'S OUR HOME.

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:44.000
AND IF WE DON'T
UNDERSTAND HOW IT WORKS

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:46.000
WE'RE GOING TO HAVE A
TOUGH TIME LIVING HERE

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:49.000
AND SURVIVING HERE ON THIS
PLANET IN THE LONG RUN.

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:00.000
THE STUDY OF VOLCANOS
REQUIRES SPATIAL ANALYSIS

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:01.000
AND VISUAL MEMORY SKILLS.

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:04.000
A SOLID FOUNDATION IN
GEOLOGY AND MATH IS ESSENTIAL.

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:08.000
VOLCANOLOGY IS A
SPECIALIZED FIELD

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:11.000
WITH MOST JOBS IN
ACADEMIA OR GOVERNMENT.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:14.000
OPTIONS FOR OTHER TYPES OF
GEOLOGISTS INCLUDE URBAN

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:19.000
PLANNING, OIL EXPLORATION,
MINING AND MORE.

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:22.000
THE MEDIAN ANNUAL SALARY
FOR ALL GEOSCIENTISTS

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:24.000
IS AROUND $69,000.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:26.000
WITHIN THE GOVERNMENT
GEOLOGISTS AVERAGE OVER

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:29.000
$83,000 A YEAR.

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:43.000
CARS, FACTORIES,
POWER PLANTS -

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:45.000
SOURCES OF POLLUTION
ARE EVERYWHERE.

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:49.000
BUT HOW MUCH DO POLLUTANTS
ACTUALLY AFFECT OUR HEALTH?

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:51.000
ENVIRONMENTAL
HEALTH SCIENTISTS

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:53.000
LIKE FREDERICA PERERA
ANSWER THAT QUESTION

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:55.000
BY DISCOVERING
THE CONNECTIONS

00:15:55.000 --> 00:15:57.000
BETWEEN TOXINS
AND DISEASE.

00:15:57.000 --> 00:15:59.000
WE'RE TALKING ABOUT
COMMON URBAN POLLUTANTS

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:02.000
FROM COMBUSTION SOURCES,
CARS, BUSES, TRUCKS,

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:05.000
THE BURNING OF ORGANIC
MATERIAL FOR POWER,

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:09.000
FOR HEAT, SO, WE GENERATE
A LOT OF THESE POLLUTANTS

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:12.000
LOCALLY RIGHT HERE
OUT ON OUR STREETS.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:15.000
THOUGH SHE'S AN EXPERT
IN HER FIELD NOW,

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:18.000
FREDERICA DIDN'T
ALWAYS PLAN ON

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:20.000
GOING INTO
ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH.

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:21.000
AFTER GRADUATING
FROM COLLEGE

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:23.000
WITH A LIBERAL
ARTS DEGREE,

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:26.000
FREDERICA TOOK TIME
TO RAISE A FAMILY.

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:28.000
WHILE CONSIDERING
GRADUATE SCHOOL,

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:30.000
A PHOTO EXHIBIT
SHE SAW IN NEW YORK

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:32.000
CHANGED THE
COURSE OF HER LIFE.

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:34.000
IT SHOWED THESE
PHOTOGRAPHS OF CHILDREN

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:37.000
WHO HAD BEEN
HARMED BECAUSE

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:41.000
THEIR MOTHERS ATE FISH
FROM THE POLLUTED BAY.

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:45.000
I WAS VERY STRUCK BY THIS
AND BEGAN THINKING ABOUT

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:48.000
HOW VERY SENSITIVE THIS
STAGE OF DEVELOPMENT IS

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:50.000
AND THAT CONCERNED ME
BECAUSE AT THE TIME

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:53.000
I ACTUALLY HAD YOUNG
CHILDREN MYSELF.

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:56.000
IN A DRAMATIC SHIFT,
FREDERICA DECIDED TO

00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:58.000
BECOME A RESEARCH
SCIENTIST, FOCUSED

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:01.000
MAINLY ON THE EFFECTS
OF AIRBORNE POLLUTANTS.

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:03.000
AS A PHD STUDENT SHE
PIONEERED THE USE OF

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:06.000
NEW METHODS FOR MEASURING
THE AMOUNT OF DAMAGE

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:07.000
CERTAIN
TOXIC POLLUTANTS

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:09.000
ACTUALLY CAUSE
TO OUR DNA.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:11.000
HER FINDINGS MIGHT LEAD
TO BROAD IMPROVEMENTS

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:13.000
IN PUBLIC POLICY.

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:17.000
I BEGAN TO SEE THAT WE
COULD DETECT THIS KIND OF

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:20.000
DAMAGE IN PEOPLE WHO
WERE PERFECTLY HEALTHY

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:22.000
AND WEREN'T JUST
CASES WITH DISEASE.

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:25.000
AND THIS DAMAGE WAS
A CHANGE IN DNA,

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:28.000
AN ACTUAL ALTERATION IN
THE GENETIC MATERIAL

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:32.000
AS A RESULT OF THIS
POLLUTANT EXPOSURE.

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:34.000
SHE DISCOVERED THAT
TOXINS CAN EVEN AFFECT

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:36.000
AN UNBORN FETUS.

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:39.000
THIS LED FREDERICA TO LAUNCH
INTERNATIONAL STUDIES

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:41.000
INVOLVING THOUSANDS
OF MOTHERS AND CHILDREN

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:43.000
TO TRACK THE IMPACT
OF THIS EXPOSURE.

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:46.000
THE CHILDREN WHO HAD MORE
EXPOSURE IN THE WOMB

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:49.000
TO THESE COMBUSTION-RELATED
AIR POLLUTANTS

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:52.000
SCORED SIGNIFICANTLY
LOWER ON THE TESTS

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:53.000
FOR MENTAL DEVELOPMENT

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:57.000
AND WERE MORE THAN TWICE,
ALMOST THREE TIMES

00:17:57.000 --> 00:18:01.000
AS LIKELY TO BE
DEVELOPMENTALLY DELAYED.

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:03.000
FREDERICA CONTINUES TO
TRAVEL AROUND THE WORLD

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:06.000
TO MEET WITH HER
INTERNATIONAL COLLEAGUES.

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:08.000
AS A TENURED PROFESSOR,
SHE ALSO SPENDS A LOT

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:11.000
OF TIME APPLYING FOR
FUNDING, AND SHE TEACHES.

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:14.000
BUT FOR FREDERICA, THE
MOST SATISFYING THING

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:16.000
ABOUT HER WORK IS
THE REAL IMPACT

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:18.000
IT CAN HAVE ON
PEOPLE'S LIVES.

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:20.000
WE DON'T JUST PUBLISH
OUR RESULTS AND SAY

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:22.000
THAT'S AN
IMPORTANT FINDING,

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:25.000
BUT WE REACH OUT TO
THE PARTICIPANTS

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:29.000
IN THE STUDY AND THE
FAMILIES TO TELL THEM

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:32.000
WHAT THEY CAN DO TO
PROTECT THEIR CHILDREN.

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:34.000
AND SHE HOPES THAT
HER WORK WILL CAUSE

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:36.000
LASTING CHANGES IN
ENVIRONMENTAL POLICY.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:39.000
THERE ARE WAYS TO CURB
AND SHARPLY REDUCE

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:41.000
THESE POLLUTANTS
SINCE THEY ARE

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:44.000
EMITTED FROM BURNING
OF FOSSIL FUELS.

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:46.000
WE CAN HAVE MUCH
MORE EFFICIENT

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:48.000
ENERGY TECHNOLOGIES.

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:51.000
WE CAN HAVE CLEANER CARS
AND TRUCKS AND BUSES.

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:53.000
FOR EXAMPLE, WE
CAN USE HYBRIDS

00:18:53.000 --> 00:18:56.000
AND CLEAN
AIR TECHNOLOGY.

00:18:56.000 --> 00:18:57.000
AND NOT ONLY DOES SHE
HAVE THE POTENTIAL

00:18:57.000 --> 00:18:59.000
TO TOUCH THE LIVES OF
THOUSANDS OF PEOPLE,

00:18:59.000 --> 00:19:02.000
SHE ALSO LOVES HER JOB.

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:03.000
SCIENCE IS LIKE...

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:05.000
IT'S DETECTIVE WORK.

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:08.000
AND IT IS INTELLECTUALLY
VERY, VERY EXCITING.

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:10.000
BUT WORKING WITH
COMMITTED PEOPLE

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:13.000
HAS BEEN ANOTHER JOY -
COMMITTED AND SMART PEOPLE

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:16.000
WHO CARE ABOUT
FINDING THE ANSWERS

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:19.000
TO HOW WE CAN BETTER
PREVENT DISEASE.

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:22.000
THAT'S BEEN A WONDERFUL
ODYSSEY FOR ME.

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:31.000
ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH
SCIENTISTS NEED TO BE

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:33.000
GOOD AT COMMUNICATING,

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:34.000
WORKING WITH DIVERSE
GROUPS OF PEOPLE,

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:37.000
AND MAKING ABSTRACT
CONNECTIONS.

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:40.000
RESEARCHERS IN THIS
FIELD PICK SPECIALTIES

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:43.000
LIKE HAZARDOUS WASTE, FOOD
PROTECTION, WATER QUALITY,

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:45.000
OR RADIATION,

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:48.000
AND OFTEN WORK CLOSELY
WITH GOVERNMENT AGENCIES.

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:50.000
THE MEDIAN SALARY FOR ALL
ENVIRONMENTAL SCIENTISTS

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:53.000
IS OVER $53,000
WITH A RANGE FROM

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:57.000
THE LOW $30'S TO
THE HIGH $80'S.

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:08.000
ERIC SANDERSON LOOKS
AROUND MANHATTAN

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:11.000
AND SEES MORE THAN
JUST THE MADDING CROWD

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:13.000
AMONG THE SKYSCRAPERS.

00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:16.000
A LANDSCAPE ECOLOGIST WITH
THE WILDLIFE CONSERVATION

00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:19.000
SOCIETY, ERIC SEES
BLACK BEARS, COUGARS,

00:20:19.000 --> 00:20:22.000
AND BEAVERS ROVING
AMONG STREAMS, WETLANDS

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:23.000
AND ROLLING HILLS.

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:27.000
WHAT ERIC SEES IS NOT
MANHATTAN, BUT MANNAHATTA

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:30.000
- THE ISLAND'S ORIGINAL
NATIVE AMERICAN NAME.

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:32.000
BY TAKING DATA FROM
HISTORICAL MAPS,

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:34.000
LAND SURVEYS AND
CORRESPONDENCE

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:36.000
AND ENTERING IT
INTO GEOGRAPHIC

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:38.000
INFORMATION SYSTEMS,
HE DEVELOPED A MODEL

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:41.000
OF WHAT "THE CITY THAT
NEVER SLEEPS" LOOKED LIKE

00:20:41.000 --> 00:20:43.000
WHEN IT WAS A
LUSH WILDERNESS

00:20:43.000 --> 00:20:45.000
INSTEAD OF A
CONCRETE JUNGLE.

00:20:45.000 --> 00:20:48.000
BY RELATING THE
PLACES WE KNOW TODAY

00:20:48.000 --> 00:20:51.000
- WHAT'S AT 59TH STREET
AND FIFTH AVENUE TODAY -

00:20:51.000 --> 00:20:53.000
TO WHAT IT WAS 400
YEARS AGO, WE START TO

00:20:53.000 --> 00:20:55.000
UNDERSTAND WHY WILDNESS
IS IMPORTANT TO US.

00:20:55.000 --> 00:20:57.000
PEOPLE REALLY
GET INTO IT

00:20:57.000 --> 00:21:00.000
BECAUSE IT'S THEIR
OWN BACKYARD.

00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:03.000
PEOPLE SEE A STREAM THAT
GOES DOWN FIFTH AVENUE

00:21:03.000 --> 00:21:05.000
AND IT SO
BLOWS THEIR MIND -

00:21:05.000 --> 00:21:07.000
HOW DO YOU RECONCILE
THOSE TWO THINGS?

00:21:07.000 --> 00:21:10.000
ERIC'S "MANNAHATTA
PROJECT" IS DRIVEN BY

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:13.000
HIS OVERARCHING GOAL
OF CONSERVATION.

00:21:13.000 --> 00:21:15.000
AS A LANDSCAPE ECOLOGIST,
HE STUDIES HOW ECOSYSTEMS

00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:17.000
INTERACT ON
A BROAD SCALE

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:20.000
AND HOW HUMAN POPULATIONS
IMPACT THE ENVIRONMENT.

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:22.000
MOST OF MY WORK AT THE
WILDLIFE CONSERVATION

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:25.000
SOCIETY IS ABOUT SAVING
WILDLIFE IN WILD PLACES

00:21:25.000 --> 00:21:26.000
ALL AROUND THE WORLD.

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:28.000
WE TRY AND HELP
LOCAL COMMUNITIES

00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:30.000
UNDERSTAND WHAT IT MEANS
TO LIVE WITH WILDLIFE

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:33.000
AND FIND SOLUTIONS FOR
THEM TO LIVE WITH WILDLIFE.

00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:35.000
ONE OF HIS PROJECTS MAPPED
THE HUMAN FOOTPRINT

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:37.000
ON A GLOBAL SCALE.

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:40.000
ERIC COMBINED INFORMATION
LIKE POPULATION DENSITY,

00:21:40.000 --> 00:21:42.000
ROADS, LAND USE, AND
LIGHTS VISIBLE FROM A

00:21:42.000 --> 00:21:45.000
SATELLITE AT NIGHT, AND
WAS ABLE TO CONCLUDE THAT

00:21:45.000 --> 00:21:49.000
HUMANS INFLUENCE 83% OF
THE EARTH'S LAND SURFACE.

00:21:49.000 --> 00:21:51.000
WHEN HE CONFINED THE
MAP TO AREAS SUITABLE

00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:55.000
FOR FARMING, THE
NUMBER GREW TO 98%.

00:21:55.000 --> 00:21:57.000
THE TOUGH PART IS
WHAT TO DO NEXT.

00:21:57.000 --> 00:21:59.000
STATISTICS LIKE THAT
FUEL ERIC'S INTEREST

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:01.000
IN CONSERVATION,
BUT CAN ALSO

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:04.000
MAKE HIM THE
BEARER OF BAD NEWS.

00:22:04.000 --> 00:22:06.000
SCIENTISTS OFTEN SAY HARD
THINGS AND MEAN THINGS

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:08.000
AND THINGS THAT
ARE HARD TO HEAR

00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:10.000
ABOUT WHAT'S HAPPENING
TO THE ENVIRONMENT,

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:12.000
AND WHAT I WANT
PEOPLE TO DO

00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:15.000
IS UNDERSTAND WHY
WE CARE SO MUCH.

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:17.000
ERIC ATTRIBUTES HIS
PASSION TO CHILDHOOD

00:22:17.000 --> 00:22:19.000
SUMMERS SPENT AT HIS
GRANDMOTHER'S CABIN

00:22:19.000 --> 00:22:21.000
DEEP IN THE
COLORADO WILDERNESS,

00:22:21.000 --> 00:22:24.000
WHERE HE AND HIS COUSINS
ROAMED FREE IN THE WOODS.

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:27.000
HE WAS ALSO INSPIRED BY A
222-MILE BACKPACKING TRIP

00:22:27.000 --> 00:22:30.000
HE TOOK WITH FRIENDS IN
HIS NATIVE CALIFORNIA.

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:32.000
TO THIS DAY HE
RECALLS THIS AS BEING

00:22:32.000 --> 00:22:34.000
THE FIRST TIME HE EVER
FELT SELF-SUFFICIENT

00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:36.000
AND TRULY CONTENT.

00:22:36.000 --> 00:22:38.000
BUT ERIC STUDIED
BIOCHEMISTRY

00:22:38.000 --> 00:22:40.000
AND FIRST WENT TO WORK
FOR A CHEMICAL COMPANY.

00:22:40.000 --> 00:22:43.000
AFTER A FEW YEARS HE
RECALLED HIS FATHER'S REGRET

00:22:43.000 --> 00:22:46.000
AT GIVING UP ON HIS FORESTRY
CAREER TO GO INTO BUSINESS.

00:22:46.000 --> 00:22:50.000
ERIC CHANGED HIS FOCUS, GOT
A PHD IN LANDSCAPE ECOLOGY,

00:22:50.000 --> 00:22:54.000
AND JOINED
THE WCS IN 1998.

00:22:54.000 --> 00:22:56.000
OUR LIVES ARE SO BUSY
AND SO FULL WITH THINGS

00:22:56.000 --> 00:22:59.000
THAT WE FORGET HOW
IMPORTANT NATURE IS TO US.

00:22:59.000 --> 00:23:02.000
HIS WORK WITH THE WCS
OFTEN INCLUDES TRAVELING

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:06.000
TO EXOTIC LOCATIONS - LIKE
MONGOLIA AND TANZANIA.

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:09.000
BACK IN NEW YORK, A
TYPICAL DAY COULD INCLUDE

00:23:09.000 --> 00:23:12.000
WORKING ON BISON RECOVERY,
RESEARCHING THE WILDLIFE

00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:14.000
POPULATION ON THE
COAST OF PATAGONIA,

00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:16.000
AND UPDATING THE
MANNAHATTA PROJECT.

00:23:16.000 --> 00:23:20.000
WE HOPE TO HAVE A THOUSAND
TO TWO THOUSAND LAYERS

00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:22.000
- ONE FOR EVERY SPECIES -

00:23:22.000 --> 00:23:24.000
EVERY VERTEBRATE SPECIES
THAT LIVED ON MANHATTAN.

00:23:24.000 --> 00:23:27.000
BY SHOWING HOW MUCH THINGS
HAVE CHANGED IN 400 YEARS,

00:23:27.000 --> 00:23:29.000
HE HOPES TO HELP
PEOPLE REALIZE THAT

00:23:29.000 --> 00:23:31.000
THE WAY WE TREAT
OUR LANDSCAPE TODAY

00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:33.000
HAS AN IMPACT ON
FUTURE GENERATIONS.

00:23:33.000 --> 00:23:36.000
THE QUESTION IS WHAT
IS MANHATTAN GOING TO

00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:37.000
LOOK LIKE 200
YEARS FROM NOW?

00:23:37.000 --> 00:23:39.000
IS IT GOING TO BE
TALLER AND TALLER

00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:40.000
AND TALLER BUILDINGS?

00:23:40.000 --> 00:23:42.000
OR ARE WE GOING TO
LEAVE SOME PLACES

00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:44.000
WHERE NATURE CAN
THRIVE AND SUPPORT US?

00:23:44.000 --> 00:23:46.000
THAT'S THE QUESTION
I'M TRYING TO ASK,

00:23:46.000 --> 00:23:48.000
AND TO HELP PEOPLE
REALIZE THAT PEOPLE

00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:50.000
200 YEARS, 400
YEARS FROM NOW

00:23:50.000 --> 00:23:53.000
INHERIT THE CONSEQUENCES
OF OUR CHOICES.

00:23:59.000 --> 00:24:01.000
KEY SKILLS IN LANDSCAPE
ECOLOGY INCLUDE

00:24:01.000 --> 00:24:03.000
SYNTHESIZING
LOTS OF DATA,

00:24:03.000 --> 00:24:06.000
KNOWLEDGE OF GEOGRAPHY AND
COMPUTER SCIENCE, AND

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:10.000
UNDERSTANDING HOW POLITICS
INFLUENCES CONSERVATION.

00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:13.000
OTHER ECOLOGY CAREER PATHS
INCLUDE CONSERVATION,

00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:16.000
LAND USE AND MANAGEMENT,
OR SPECIALIZING

00:24:16.000 --> 00:24:19.000
IN A PARTICULAR
TYPE OF ECOSYSTEM.

00:24:19.000 --> 00:24:22.000
ECOLOGISTS IN ACADEMICS
AVERAGE $60,000 A YEAR,

00:24:22.000 --> 00:24:24.000
WHILE THOSE
OUTSIDE ACADEMICS

00:24:24.000 --> 00:24:27.000
AVERAGE $71,000 ANNUALLY.

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:35.000
FROM GEOLOGY
TO METEOROLOGY,

00:24:35.000 --> 00:24:38.000
OCEANOGRAPHY TO ECOLOGY,
A CAREER IN EARTH SCIENCES

00:24:38.000 --> 00:24:41.000
IS A CAREER OF EXPLORATION,
LEADING TO DISCOVERIES

00:24:41.000 --> 00:24:43.000
THAT CAN CONNECT THE
PRESENT TO THE PAST

00:24:43.000 --> 00:24:46.000
AND CARVE A PATH
TO THE FUTURE.

00:24:46.000 --> 00:24:48.000
YOUR JOURNEY IN THE EARTH
SCIENCES COULD WIND FROM

00:24:48.000 --> 00:24:51.000
THE TOPS OF MOUNTAINS TO
THE DEPTHS OF THE OCEANS,

00:24:51.000 --> 00:24:54.000
THROUGH URBAN CITYSCAPES
OR REMOTE LANDSCAPES,

00:24:54.000 --> 00:24:56.000
BUT IT WILL CERTAINLY
START WITH A COMMITMENT

00:24:56.000 --> 00:24:57.000
TO EDUCATION.

00:24:57.000 --> 00:25:01.000
WITH A BACHELOR'S
DEGREE, YOU CAN TEACH,

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:04.000
WORK AS A LAB TECHNICIAN
OR FIELD RESEARCHER,

00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:08.000
OR TAKE A JOB IN AN INDUSTRY
SUCH AS MINING OR OIL.

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:12.000
WITH A MASTER'S DEGREE,
YOU CAN LEAD RESEARCH

00:25:12.000 --> 00:25:15.000
IN GOVERNMENT OR
INDUSTRY LABS.

00:25:15.000 --> 00:25:17.000
GRADUATE STUDY IN ANOTHER
AREA COULD LAUNCH A CAREER

00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:21.000
IN POLICY, LAW,
OR JOURNALISM.

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:24.000
GETTING A PHD TAKES
FIVE TO SEVEN YEARS,

00:25:24.000 --> 00:25:27.000
THOUGH MOST UNIVERSITIES
WILL PAY YOUR WAY

00:25:27.000 --> 00:25:29.000
AND REQUIRES ANOTHER
TWO TO FOUR YEARS

00:25:29.000 --> 00:25:32.000
OF PAID
POSTDOCTORAL WORK.

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:35.000
FOR PHD'S THE
SKY'S THE LIMIT.

00:25:35.000 --> 00:25:38.000
AND WHETHER YOU
STUDY ICY GLACIERS

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:40.000
OR MOLTEN
LAVA FLOWS;

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:43.000
THE EYE OF THE STORM OR
THE CORE OF THE PLANET,

00:25:43.000 --> 00:25:46.000
YOU MAY JUST UNCOVER
LIFE-SAVING INFORMATION

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:48.000
ALONG THE WAY.